r rent. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Many are worried for those households who were</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> already in arrears before the changes came in who are finding it harder to keep to suspended possession agreements now that they must pay the agreed rent plus some.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Staffing costs have increased significantly as a result of the need to provide greater s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">upport to tenants as well as to ensure staff have a thorough understanding of the changes. Higher levels of contact and support are required both as preventative measures and to help residents through increasing levels of crises. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">North Hertfordshire Homes’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">housing management </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">yearly </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">staffing costs have increased by</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> £134,000 (1.6%</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> annually due to the need to recruit specialist posts and increase staffing levels generally. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Some properties have been freed up and there is an increase in the number of mutual ex</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">changes as people who want to downsize have matched with people who want bigger properties. In the last five months alone </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Hightown Praetorian &amp; Churches Housing Association </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">(Hightown) has reported 26% more exchanges than it did in the entirety of last year</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, an experience that has been replicated across the county. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Circle Housing Group</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> provides House Exchange, the country’s largest not-for-profit web-based mutual exchange service. House Exchange allows for home swaps between </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">any council and housing associati</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">on tenant with the right to mutually exchange by</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> automatically matching house-seekers with a home that meet their needs. Since the Under-Occupation Penalty – or the so called ‘bedroom tax’ – was introduced in April 2013, the number of registrations to Hous</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">e Exchange website, </span><a href="http://www.houseexchange.org.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.houseexchange.org.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, have increased by 26%. The majority of those registering on the site, around 26%, are looking to move to a larger property </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">but the number looking to down-size has increased as a proportion of registrations to around 10%. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Although mutual exchange is an important tool in addressing welfare reform, it still remains the case that there are not enough one bedroom properties for te</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">nants to down-size into. Indeed some research undertaken by the University of Cambridge’s Centre for Housing and Planning Research on behalf of East 7 showed that, even </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">If all appropriate re-lets were reserved to allow under occupying tenants to move to sm</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">aller homes, it would still take nearly eight years to re-house all current tenants who </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">require a downsize to 1 bedroom accommodation.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">What is more, mutual exchange</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> expensive </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">for housing associations:</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Grand Union Housing Group </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">calculates </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">for each </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">transaction, they incur an average cost</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">of £550.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Some housing associations have seen an increase in voids, with particular difficulties in letting family homes e.g. 3 bed flats and houses in rural locations. One member, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Estuary</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> points to a 38% increase in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">voids in the first four months of 2013/14 compared to the same period the previous year, stimulated by transfers responding in part to welfare reform. </span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.44pt; padding-left:2.56pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What impact do you anticipate the changes having over the coming months for you as housing associations?</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The trends already outlined are likely to continue, with increased costs and bad debts, and reduced income. There will continue to be uncertainty over how tenants will respond both in the short and longer term. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Housing associations are likely to have to</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> increase the number of evictions for non-payment of rent as well as dealing with the consequences of uncertainty around direct payments. </span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.44pt; padding-left:2.56pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What impact have the changes had to date on the people you house, particularly those in vulnerable groups (such as pe</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ople with disabilities and families with children)?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The biggest impact has been the increased risk of family financial hardship with greater pressure on household budgets. The emotional impact and increased stress, particularly for vulnerable groups is not</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> to be underestimated, as the following case studies show.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">In particular, customers with disabilities have needed additional support in requesting DHP from their local authority or reviewing their options where they live in adapted housing. Those with fami</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">lies who have been allocated a particular size of house by the local authority but now face the ‘bedroom tax’ reduction in their housing benefit have struggled to understand and cope with this.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">North Herfordshire Homes</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> reports that 676 of their 8,000 gene</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ral needs tenants are affected by the ‘bedroom tax’, with 119 deemed to be under-occupying by two rooms or more. Arrears have increased for 409 (62%) of those affected, averaging £10.80. 14 possession orders have been obtained and two eviction warrants sou</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ght for these cases. 150 of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">North Herfordshire Homes’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> tenants are waiting to downsize, but only 38 have been able to. 161 households are unable to move due to rent arrears or a possession order being in place. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">For those in the examples, the likely outcomes are that the costs to the tax payer will far outweigh the relative saving through imposing the ‘bedroom tax’, and do not </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">necessarily make better use of our stock. Affected tenants have to make choices about ho</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">w money is spent where previously those choices were made for them. These decisions become more acute when there simply is not enough money to cover some very basic outgoings. This will become more acute when direct payment is implemented.   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#d9d9d9; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Case studies</span><br /><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#d9d9d9; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">A lives in a 3B and is deemed to be under occupying by 2 bedrooms with a 25% deduction in HB. He suffers from multiple sclerosis and in the absence of any family support receives 24 hour care from a professional carer. His carer only receives 5 hours pai</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">d care a week as she lives in the property and so does not contribute to the rent. A is not able to move unless we fully facilitate the move and the Local Authority (or Estuary) invests appropriately to replace his hoist and hospital bed and moves the equi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">pment needed for his daily needs.  We have applied for DHP for A and at least expect his deduction to be reduced to 14%.  </span></p><p style="background-color:#d9d9d9; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Couple </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> have a number of health issues and between them receive low level DLA, some Employment and Support Allowance and Carer’s All</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">owance for a daughter with Cystic Fibrosis. The property has minor adaptations and equipment for their daughter. The equipment is kept in the 3rd bedroom which is considered a ‘box-room’. The daughter’s income support payments have been taken into consider</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ation in the council tax support which has resulted in benefit being cut from 100% to only a few pounds. DHP has been awarded for 3 months. The couple need a very large 2 bed or face placing their daughter in a care home to widen their options to a one-bed</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">room. The likelihood of securing alternative accommodation in 3 months is very low.</span></p><p style="background-color:#d9d9d9; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">C has learning difficulties. Her 11, 13 &amp; 14 year old children are in care but as she is in regular contact, there was a hope that at least one will be able to live with he</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">r in her 2-bedroom property. Downsizing removes the hope of this. It has been some time since she has worked and although she has been invited to the job club, it is not clear whether the job club’s generic approach will be of assistance.</span></p><p style="background-color:#d9d9d9; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">D occupies a 3B o</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">n her own as her lodger recently moved out. D has poor health but was turned down for</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> Employment Support Allowance. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We have no one bedroom properties in her area and so we have been unable to offer any likelihood of a transfer. D does not have access to th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">e internet to make a claim, and at our visit had no credit on her phone or bus fare to contact/visit and make an application for JSA. D’s JSA will provide £71 per week income however outgoings equate to over £100 including £26.41 for the shortfall, £2.50 c</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ouncil tax, £40 gas and electricity, £30 food and toiletries and £5 for her phone. An application for DHP has now been made for D whilst we assess what assistance we can give her</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="background-color:#d9d9d9; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">E is a victim of extreme domestic violence</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">has two girls aged</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">14. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">After </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">E </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">suffered 20 years of physical abuse the police finally removed her husband from the property last year. The abuse had a lasting effect on her eldest daughter, X, who is diagnosed with autism and has a DLA award for this. X is self-harming on a dail</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">y basis by cutting her arms and legs. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">wants </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to downsize as she simply ca</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">nnot afford the £13.55 per week—s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">he is trying to find a property with a dining room or a big enough room to split into two. She cannot put the girls together as the eldest one needs </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">her own space and she doesn’t want the youngest copying her self-destructive behaviour. In a year and a half when the eldest </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">turns 16 they will no longer be affected by the under-occupancy charge, but </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> cannot afford to wait. </span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">In efforts to stretch budgets tenants are being proactive but choices can have a negative impact. The use of food banks and simply not being able to afford to buy food is seen much more regularly amongst our tenants. In addition the use of non-traditional </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">loan sources has continued. Some tenants have found lodgers and some have found work as a way out of the situation. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Under the new system tenants have less choice. They are limited by what size properties housing benefit will fund, irrespective of what the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">y may need. This in turn has led to a more stressful experience. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Community and family stability will also be impacted. More are moving as people take a two bedroom house now whilst they have young children, but they will need to get a bigger home when they are older. </span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.44pt; padding-left:2.56pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What impact do you anticipate the changes having ove</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">r the coming months for the people you house? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The trends outlined in answer to Q3 will continue. In addition, with the roll-out of Universal Credit, many tenants who have never managed their own housing costs will need support in dealing with the amount a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">nd frequency of Universal Credit payments. They will need to learn to budget monthly rather than weekly or fortnightly and will have more payments to make.</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.44pt; padding-left:2.56pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Have you developed any new or innovative responses to the changes and could these be replicated by o</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ther housing associations? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Under the new system it is important that members can spot problems before they escalate, helping tenants to manage any problems, and providing much greater support. To achieve this all members have had to look at their services</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, staffing, funding support, and procedures, to ensure a holistic response. We provide further detail on how they are innovating below. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Members are working with tenants to help them to move. Initiatives range from pro-actively identifying those tenants un</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">der-occupying and who would benefit from a move, to mutual exchange events (speed dating for transfer applicants), and home visits to households to advise customers on the options available to them in reaction to the introduction of the ‘bedroom tax’. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">High</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">town</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> has even given its Housing Director discretion to approve transfers if households are in rent arrears due to the Government’s welfare reforms. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Members are investing in the training and up skilling of staff so that they can provide more support in-per</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">son to tenants. This includes the creation of new roles, such as </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">bpha</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">’s Pre-tenancy Officers to carry out income and expenditure assessments to discuss the true affordability of taking on a new home with prospective tenants, and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Project Neighbourhood Offic</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ers to carry out additional work looking into the impact of changes within a neighbourhood, and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">North Hertfordshire Homes</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">’ specialist advice posts for under-occupation and mutual exchange, and welfare benefits advice. Housing management staff’s roles have </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">changed to provide early and more effective intervention on rent arrears.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Employment support and money advice services are in particular demand: </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">bpha</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> is experiencing greater number of referrals to its employment support and money advice services, as tenant</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s focus on getting into work and dealing with debt;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Estuary </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">has increased the number of employment workshops, support with completing DHP applications. In addition, more general budgeting assistance is also being provided. , </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Circle Housing Group </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">is investi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ng £1 million each year in financial inclusion services</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">North Hertfordshire Homes </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">has introduced budgeting assistance into its support work, providing advice on cooking, food shopping on a budget and information on food banks. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Indeed, concerns regardin</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">g the provision of food have become so acute that some of our members have started to contribute </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">directly </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to foodbanks. South Northants Homes, a subsidiary of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Grand Union Housing Group</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">became </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">involved in the establishment of a foodbank in Towcester when t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">hey </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">discovered referrals of their tenants to foodbanks had doubled</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">5.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Members are helping tenants to navigate the new welfare system and to receive the right benefits. Initiatives include simple tools such as the provision of a benefits calculator on the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">E</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">stuary </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">website to fuller support such as </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">North Hertfordshire Homes </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">establishing close working links with housing benefits teams to facilitate applications for discretionary payments and assist tenants with their applications. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">5.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">One worrying aspect of the re</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">forms is the digital exclusion caused by moving many aspects of the benefit system online. When </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Circle Housing Group </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">conducted a survey in anticipation of the welfare reforms, they discovered 45% of their tenants did not have access to internet at home. In</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> response to the problems raised by the Government’s ‘digital-by-default’ approach, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">North Hertfordshire Homes</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> are recruiting ‘digital champions’ to assist claimants without access to personal computers or unfamiliar with how to use online forms and recycli</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ng PCs and laptops to equip households for digital benefits claims. Public use points for PCs are also being established in neighbourhood and communal facilitates, supported by volunteers or staff. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">5.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">There are also perverse consequences within the system. D</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ue to necessity, one association is exploring with housing benefit teams how to maximise the number of new supported housing tenants that can receive housing benefit payment under the vulnerability criteria and exploring fully the application of ‘exempt ac</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">commodation’. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">5.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Members are also investing their surpluses in removing blockages within the system. For example, a tenant may wish to downsize to avoid a reduction in benefit, but under normal circumstances this would not be permitted if they were in arrear</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s. Members are adopting a more flexible response as well as providing financial incentives. For example, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">bpha</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> has a “room to move” policy, creating the financial room to move by </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">helping tenants with moving costs and also allowing tenants who have rent arre</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ars to move home with a package of help and conditions. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">5.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Members are partnering with other organisations to secure financial services which can support their tenants. As part of this work they are also increasing financial inclusion training so that staff </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">are better able to advise. A number of our members, including </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Flagship</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Estuary </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">North Hertfordshire Homes</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, are partnering with Credit Unions to provide managed accounts for those without bank accounts, and helping to promote these so that there is an e</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">asy route for people to access them. In addition, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">North Hertfordshire Homes </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">is providing increased funding to the Black Squirrel Credit Union so that loans to tenants are underwritten on more favourable terms</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.44pt; padding-left:2.56pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are your views on the treatment of housing costs within Universal Credit? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Members’ preference is for the housing element to be clearly defined and not lumped in with a single payment. Reasons range from the efficient functioning of the system, to the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> needs of the tenant. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">There is recognition that the logic that underpins Universal Credit and the basic principles of empowering people, replicating the way wages work and giving people responsibility are sound. We can understand the reasoning behind hous</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ing costs being included, but not the insistence on it being on a compulsory basis. For those people who wish to have their housing costs deducted at source they should be able to do so. There are parallels for those with a mortgage, where the building soc</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">iety or bank requires a direct debit to be in place for automatic payment. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">It is important to balance the policy objective of fostering good financial behaviour with the importance of a secure home. Ensuring that rent is paid not only provides stability but reduce the costs to the tax payer of homelessness, children’s care servic</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">es, schemes to address rough sleeping and cost to the NHS. Given that there is clear potential for tenants to use tax payer funded benefit on costs other than rent, for those wishing to avoid that risk there should remain an option for rent to be paid dire</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ctly to a social landlord.    </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">There are also some unanswered questions around how the housing cost element will work in practice. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Particularly around defaulting payments to landlords where arrears accrue, the process for payments reverting to customers, f</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">requency of allowing the default, etc.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">It is particularly hard for any tenant to recover from accruing two months of rent arrears and it can have a very long term impact on their life if this is allowed to happen – a safety mechanism needs to exist and be </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">properly thought through.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">For the housing associations, with careful management the impact of the inevitable passage back and forward from payment to tenants to payment to landlords as people fall into arrears and then recover can be managed but clarity </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">is needed. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">In addition, policy makers need to be aware that the increased administrative burden combined with the general increase in financial pressures, will inevitably lead to higher </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">rent arrears which will restrict housing association’s ability to bor</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">row from banks etc.  The reduction in surpluses caused by reduced income will compound this and as a result we will be able to do less, build less homes and provide less good services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> ‘</span><a href="http://www.east7.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/downloads/2013/06/East-7-CCHPR-report-med-res-for-printing.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Social Housing in the East: Challenges for the region and implications for the UK</span></a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">’, Cambridge Centre for Housing and Planning Rese</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">arch, University of Cambridge, 2013</span></p></body></html>